    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-22T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-22T04:00:00-05:00" n="427"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d427">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/11–2244: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Alexander C. Kirk</persName>,
                        Political Adviser, Allied Force Headquarters, to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caserta</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-22T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 22, 1944—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 23—11:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1442. General Koenig<note n="57" xml:id="d427fn57">Brig. Gen. Egmont F. Koenig,
                        Chief, American delegation, Allied Joint Military Mission for
                        Bulgaria.</note> reports that three of his officers, accompanied by Soviet
                    officers, left Sofia November 20th to visit Macedonia and Thrace to verify
                    withdrawal of Bulgarian troops from Greek territory. They are expected to return
                    about November 23rd at which time General Koenig proposes to sign a codicil to
                    the protocol already signed by Soviet and British representatives attesting
                    Bulgarian compliance with pre-armistice conditions. Koenig expects to have
                    accomplished his mission within a week. He reports Barnes’ arrival on November
                    19th and states that his mission is now being guided by Barnes’ advice.</p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated to Moscow as No. 132.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
